'''Mount Misery Battery''' was an artillery battery situated on the Upper Ridge of the [[Rock of Gibraltar]]. It was situated at Mount Misery, one of the peaks of the Rock. In 1901 its name was changed to [[Breakneck Battery]] at the suggestion of Major-General [[John Slade (British Army officer)|Sir John Slade]] of the [[Royal Artillery]]. Slade was to go on command British troops in Egypt from 1903 to 1905.<ref name=slade>{{cite journal|title=Sir John Slade, The Hero of Maiwand|journal=The Colonist|date=6 September 1913|page=5|url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=TC19130906.2.44.1|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref>  Following his suggestion in 1899 that it would be a suitable position to accommodate a long-range coastal defence gun, a [[BL 9.2 inch gun Mk IX–X|9.2-inch breech-loading Mark X]] gun on a Mark V mounting was installed in 1906.<ref name="Hughes308">[[#Hughes|Hughes]], p. 308</ref>

